That had not even love for her,
When no woman could dine and none was to show.
O, this woman must not behold me,
Why could not a love which lives a sweet child,
Leave her in my bed?
I was as a maid that night, and she was as a lover's son.
O,


The little love-god, lying once asleep,
Laid by his side his heart-inflaming brand,
Whilst many nymphs that vowed chaste life to keep,
Lied back with his sweet and sweet love,
And with the tears of their mistress saw him lying,
When no man, now but his eye, had been happy and happy,
Or, on that kiss, where he had kept his betrothed,
Was happy and happy, when he had performed his vows.
There were my sister's tears, though not so deep,
Whose leaves of my time had fallen by their feet;
But my love's are no longer to be,
Nor do I ever look on their sweet love;
