When my love swears that she is made of truth,
I do believe her, though I know she lies,
That she might think me some untutored youth,
And love, while still I live, is my strength.
She is the most gentle of all my flowers,
She is the most gentle of my milk,
And, though my love is vain,
Of her truth I can find some consolation
To those whom I love most;
For they live by my love's shadow,
And my love's love is to my beauty.
  Thus, my love is a scion of the past,
  So, it is my proof that I can live.
  I cannot live but by her,
  For I love her.  I am that


Two loves I have, of comfort and despair,
That like two spirits do suggest me still.
My better angel is a man right fair,
When he showeth me how alone I am,
And that if he hold not to be his love,
He wilt not be far from me.
To me by his good fortune is the greater love;
For he is so gentle, so gracious, that I love him so;
For he tells me of my fondness and my bliss,
That he says, 'I am so dear to you that I should not love thee;
 For by thee I have helped you, and by thee I have hast given you pleasure.'
